---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Do I Need a Website for My Small Business in NZ? — SiteGenius" description="7 compelling reasons why your NZ small business needs a website in 2026. Address the Facebook-only objection and learn what a professional website actually does for your bottom line.">
  <article class="pt-32 pb-24">
    <div class="container-custom max-w-4xl">
      <!-- Article Header -->
      <header class="mb-16 text-center">
        <span class="text-neon-cyan font-bold tracking-widest uppercase text-sm mb-4 block">Small Business</span>
        <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-black mb-8 leading-tight">
          Do I Need a Website for My <span class="gradient-text">Small Business</span> in NZ?
        </h1>
        <p class="text-xl text-muted-200">
          Short answer: yes. Long answer? Read on for 7 reasons that'll make it a no-brainer.
        </p>
      </header>

      <!-- Hero Image -->
      <div class="mb-16 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden border border-white/[0.06]">
        <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1460925895917-afdab827c52f?w=1200&h=600&fit=crop" alt="Small business owner reviewing their website analytics on a laptop" class="w-full h-64 md:h-80 object-cover" loading="lazy" />
      </div>

      <!-- Article Content -->
      <div class="prose prose-lg prose-invert max-w-none">
        <div class="glass p-8 mb-12 rounded-3xl border-neon-cyan/20">
          <p class="text-lg font-medium text-space-800 leading-relaxed m-0 text-muted-100">
            It's 2026, and roughly 93% of Kiwi consumers research products and services online before making a purchase. If your business doesn't have a website, you're not just missing out on potential customers — you're actively sending them to your competitors. Whether you run a cafe in Wellington, a cleaning business in Hamilton, or a boutique in Queenstown, here's why a website is no longer optional.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-12 mb-6 text-space-900">Reason 1: You're Open 24/7</h2>
        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-6">
          Your shop might close at 5pm, but your website never does. Customers browse at 10pm on a Tuesday, during their lunch break, or at 6am before work. A website means your business is always available — answering questions, showcasing products, and capturing enquiries even while you sleep.
        </p>
        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-6">
          Think about it: if someone needs your service at 9pm on a Sunday and you don't have a website, they'll find the business that does. That's a customer gone, and you'll never know they were looking.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-12 mb-6 text-space-900">Reason 2: Credibility and Trust</h2>
        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-6">
          In 2026, not having a website is a red flag. Fair or not, consumers associate a professional website with a legitimate, established business. A well-designed site with testimonials, clear services, and professional photos says "we take our business seriously."
        </p>
        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-6">
          Studies show that 75% of consumers judge a company's credibility based on their website design. First impressions matter — and for most of your potential customers, your website <em>is</em> the first impression.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-12 mb-6 text-space-900">Reason 3: Google Is the New Yellow Pages</h2>
        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-6">
          Remember the Yellow Pages? That thick book that showed up on your doorstep every year? Google is that now — except it's used by millions of New Zealanders every single day. When someone types "coffee shop Ponsonby" or "accountant Tauranga," Google shows them businesses with websites first.
        </p>
        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-6">
          Without a website, your business is essentially invisible in the most important marketplace that exists. A website combined with a <a href="/blog/google-business-profile-nz" class="text-neon-cyan hover:underline">Google Business Profile</a> makes sure you show up when local customers are searching for exactly what you offer.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-12 mb-6 text-space-900">Reason 4: You Control the Narrative</h2>
        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-6">
          On social media, algorithms decide who sees your content. On review sites, anyone can say anything. But on your own website? You control the message. You choose what to highlight, which testimonials to feature, and how to present your brand.
        </p>
        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-6">
          Your website is owned media. It's yours. No algorithm changes, no platform shutdowns, no rule changes that tank your visibility overnight. It's the one digital asset you fully control.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-12 mb-6 text-space-900">Reason 5: It Saves You Time</h2>
        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-6">
          How many times a week do you answer the same questions? "What are your hours?" "Do you deliver to my area?" "How much does X cost?" A website handles all of that automatically. An FAQ page, a services page with pricing, and a contact page with your hours can cut your repetitive phone calls and messages in half.
        </p>
        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-6">
          That's time you can spend actually running your business instead of being a human answering machine.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-12 mb-6 text-space-900">Reason 6: Your Competitors Have One</h2>
        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-6">
          This one's simple: if your competitor has a website and you don't, guess who's getting the customer? It's not about being better — it's about being visible. When two businesses offer the same service at the same quality, the one with the professional online presence wins every time.
        </p>
        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-6">
          In fact, having a great website when your competitors have mediocre ones is a massive competitive advantage. It's one of the fastest ways to stand out in a crowded NZ market. Check out our <a href="/services" class="text-neon-cyan hover:underline">web design services</a> to see how we help businesses stand out.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-12 mb-6 text-space-900">Reason 7: It's More Affordable Than You Think</h2>
        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-6">
          The number one objection we hear is cost. And we get it — when you're running a small business, every dollar counts. But a professional website doesn't have to cost thousands upfront anymore.
        </p>
        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-6">
          With subscription models like <a href="/pricing" class="text-neon-cyan hover:underline">SiteGenius</a>, you can get a custom-designed, professionally built website from just $79/month — less than what most businesses spend on coffee for the office. That includes hosting, security, updates, and support. For a full cost comparison, read our guide on <a href="/blog/how-much-does-a-website-cost-in-nz" class="text-neon-cyan hover:underline">how much a website costs in NZ</a>.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-12 mb-6 text-space-900">"But I Just Use Facebook..."</h2>
        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-6">
          We hear this a lot, and it's worth addressing head-on. A Facebook page is <em>not</em> a replacement for a website. Here's why:
        </p>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 my-10 not-prose">
          <div class="glass-hover p-6 rounded-2xl">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-red-400 mb-3">Facebook Limitations</h3>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-muted-200 text-sm">
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-red-400 font-bold">x</span> Only 2-5% of your followers see your posts</li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-red-400 font-bold">x</span> You don't own the platform — they can change the rules anytime</li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-red-400 font-bold">x</span> Limited design and branding options</li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-red-400 font-bold">x</span> Doesn't rank well on Google for local searches</li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-red-400 font-bold">x</span> Looks unprofessional as your only presence</li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-red-400 font-bold">x</span> Can't customise the user experience</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="glass-hover p-6 rounded-2xl border border-neon-cyan/30">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-emerald-500 mb-3">Your Own Website</h3>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-muted-200 text-sm">
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-emerald-500 font-bold">+</span> 100% of visitors see your content</li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-emerald-500 font-bold">+</span> You own it — nobody can take it away</li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-emerald-500 font-bold">+</span> Full control over branding and design</li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-emerald-500 font-bold">+</span> Ranks on Google and brings in organic traffic</li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-emerald-500 font-bold">+</span> Builds credibility and professionalism</li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-2"><span class="text-emerald-500 font-bold">+</span> Tailored to convert visitors into customers</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-6">
          Don't get us wrong — Facebook is a great marketing tool. Use it alongside your website. Post content, engage with followers, and link back to your website for the details. But relying on Facebook alone is like building your house on rented land.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-12 mb-6 text-space-900">What About Instagram, TikTok, or Marketplace?</h2>
        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-6">
          Same story. Social platforms are rented space. They're brilliant for marketing and engagement, but they should all point back to your website — your home base. Algorithms change, platforms rise and fall (remember Bebo?), but your website is constant.
        </p>
        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-6">
          Plus, social media is designed to keep people scrolling — not to convert them into your customers. A website is designed with one purpose: to turn visitors into leads or sales.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-12 mb-6 text-space-900">NZ Small Business Stats That Might Surprise You</h2>
        <ul class="space-y-4 mb-8 text-muted-200">
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="text-neon-cyan font-bold mt-1">→</span>
            <span><strong>97%</strong> of consumers search online for local businesses.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="text-neon-cyan font-bold mt-1">→</span>
            <span><strong>70%</strong> of small business websites in NZ are either outdated or perform poorly on mobile.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="text-neon-cyan font-bold mt-1">→</span>
            <span><strong>53%</strong> of mobile users leave a site that takes more than 3 seconds to load.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="text-neon-cyan font-bold mt-1">→</span>
            <span><strong>88%</strong> of consumers who search locally on their phone visit a related store within a week.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold mt-12 mb-6 text-space-900">The Verdict</h2>
        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-6">
          If your small business serves customers — any customers — you need a website. It's not about being tech-savvy or following trends. It's about being findable, looking credible, and making it easy for people to choose you over the competition.
        </p>
        <p class="text-muted-200 mb-10">
          The good news? Getting a professional website has never been easier or more affordable. You don't need to learn code, hire an expensive agency, or spend weeks figuring it out. Services like SiteGenius exist specifically to take the hassle out of it for busy Kiwi business owners.
        </p>

        <!-- CTA Inside Blog -->
        <div class="mt-16 p-10 bg-gradient-to-r from-neon-cyan/10 to-neon-purple/10 rounded-3xl border border-white/10 text-center text-space-900">
          <h3 class="text-3xl font-black mb-4 text-muted-100">Get Your Business Online From $79/mo</h3>
          <p class="text-lg text-muted-200 mb-8 max-w-xl mx-auto">Professional website, hosting, and support — all sorted. No upfront costs, no tech headaches. Just a website that works for your business.</p>
          <a href="/get-a-quote" class="btn-primary">Get Your Free Quote</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
